tspan.tspan: Seru Suara is an interactive experience that facilitates
the discovery of the scales, grammar and general aesthetic
of Gamelan through a gamified experience.
A music genre native to Southeast Asia, and particularly
Indonesia, Gamelan is played today by ensembles around the
world. It has been a source of fascination and influence
in the West for centuries, and has influenced famous
composers such as Claude Debussy. It is also often found
unexpectedly in popular culture (such as the Akira
original soundtrack).
Despite this, few people know of Gamelan, and even less
understand the principles behind the music. In fact,
museum exhibits about it often fail to convey much beyond
the fascination naturally exerted by the instruments
themselves. While the exhibit might have explicatory
signage, an audio recording, or maybe even video, visitors
will still have a passive experience, and mostly remember
the striking appearance of shining metal and intricate
woodwork. It is notably difficult to find qualified
teachers outside of Indonesia, and Gamelan remains a niche
interest in most places outside of the Indo-Malay
archipelago.
In order to allow a general audience to break through and
understand a completely different musical language, Seru
Suara proposes a 30 minutes experience that progressively
brings the player to a basic understanding of the music.
In particular the game will highlight one of the specific
scales used in gamelan, and basic elements of rhythm. It
uses AI pose detection technology to allow players to
interact using their body, allowing for an actual practice
without the requirements of a teacher or interacting with
hard to find and expensive instruments.
Our UX research, during which we conducted interviews with
both music practitioners and the general public,
highlighted several important findings.
- While all interviewees were familiar with Western
musical conventions, few knew about other musical
traditions.
- All interviewees agreed that practice matters a lot when
learning music, and that theory alone cannot allow for a
proper understanding of the principles.
- Most people naturally associate visuals with music.
While a small number of interviewees had narrative based
visions, involving detailed representations of real life
settings and a story, the vast majority of our
interviewees described fluid and colourful visuals.
The experience is a web application, built with state of
the art technologies in AI pose detection (mediapipe), GPU
accelerated graphics (threlte/three.js) and DSP
(elementary audio). The experience can run locally without
access to the internet, but requires a modern browser
(Chrome or Firefox) to run in.
It is materialised as a large screen facing the player,
connected to a computer with a webcam aimed at the them.
Standby mode
The screen displays slowly moving out of focus shapes,
while sounds derived from Gamelan resonate with no
particular structure.
Onboarding
When a person is detected by the system, in focus shapes
appear. An outline of the persons body is shown, and
their right hand is highlighted. The user is let to play
with this state for a short while before moving to the
next step.
A ball like object appears in focus, and pulsates to
attract the attention of the player, when they bring their
right hand to the ball it attaches to their hand and
starts following it.
Another object appears in focus: it is one key of the
instrument we will learn how to play. It pulsates to let
the player bring their hand (with the ball attached to it)
to the key. As the ball collides with the key, the note
resonates and visuals indicate success, encouraging the
user in the right path of interaction with the experience.
As the ball bounced from the key after the collision, it
has detached from the players hand (which did not touch
anything), it pulsates again and the user must grab it
back. This bouncing / grabbing dynamic will be the basis
of the gamified experience.
The next key has now appeared and the action can be
repeated. The player will hence reveal the 5 keys and hear
the 5 notes of the scale.
Game
Once the full scale has been revealed, the experience
moves to the actual game sequence, where real pieces will
progressively be introduced and performed on the rhythm by
the player.
End
After all the scripted parts have been accomplished by the
player, or if they walk away from the experience, Seru
Suara fades back to standby mode.
Note: While the project is meant to use loudspeakers to
allow for an audience to enjoy the experience while it is
being played, it can easily be adapted to using headphones
in order to fit the requirements for Snar Project Area.
Team
Seru Suara is built by an international team of artists,
scholars, and creative technologists based in Singapore,
who have all met through their shared interest for
Gamelan.
Gaetan Boissons work has been shown in the Netherlands
and Singapore, with projects related to deep learning and
the image, as well as artificial intelligence and culture.
He started playing Balinese gamelan with Giri Kedaton in
Montreal ten years ago, and has been learning ever seen,
with ensembles such as Puspawarna in Paris, Singamurti in
Singapore, as well as Javanese Gamelan with Singa Nglaras
in Singapore.
Jan Mrazek is a scholar with a long connection to Gamelan.
Currently on a sabbatical he is taking time for his
research into new ways of introducing people to Gamelan.
He is the director of the Singa Nglaras Gamelan ensemble
at the National University of Singapore.
SKALA is a music company helmed by Rosmainy Buang, a
practitioner of gamelan music (Javanese, Sundanese and
Balinese gamelan). The name SKALA has multiple meanings,
amongst them, it can refer to a musical scale (skala
musik), a ladder (
), or the tangible, sensorial,
world of aesthetics (sekala).
